Color and Size

In this section we will use the cities dataset. In the code below, produce a scatter plot with longitude on the x-axis and latitude on the y-axis. Make the points scale with the size of the cityâ€™s population.

cities %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_point(aes(x = lon, y = lat, size = population))

What region(s) seem to have the highest concentration of large cities? Answer: Most of the largest cities are in Indian and China.

Below, repeat the same plot but now scale the color (not the size) of the points based on the population.

cities %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_point(aes(x = lon, y = lat, color = population))

Which of these two plots (color or size) do you find easier to read? Why? Answer: With the default scale, I find the size plot much easier to read because the default continuous scale is really quite bad.

In the code below, plot the cities data with the city longitude on the x-axis and latitude on the y-axis. Color the points based on the continent the city is in and make the size proportional to the population.

cities %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_point(aes(x = lon, y = lat, color = continent, size = population))

What â€œholesâ€ in the map exist? That is, what are some large regions have no cities in the dataset that you tend to expect to find on a map? Answer: There are no large cities in the region that I belive Russia occupies, nor in Northern Africa.

Group Aesthetic

In this section, we will use the us_three dataset. In the code below we are going to produce a line plot with year on the x-axis and population on the y-axis. To do this, use the geom_line geometry.

us_three %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_line(aes(x = year, y = population))

You should see a strange plot that seems to have a jagged, comb-like pattern to it. Below, repeat this plot but add a points layer that is colored by the city name (do not add color yet to the lines)

us_three %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_line(aes(x = year, y = population)) +
    geom_point(aes(x = year, y = population, color = city))

Can you see whatâ€™s happening now? The line plot is drawing a single line, from the smallest year to the largest year, without ever lifting up its pen. It is connecting across time and space, producing a plot that is nearly meaningless (or at least, very hard to interpret).

In the code below, produce a line plot with year on the x-axis and population on the y-axis. Color the lines by city. Do not include a points layer.

us_three %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_line(aes(x = year, y = population, color = city))

This plot should now look a lot nicer as it shows a different line for each city. To understand what is going on, produce the same plot in the code below, but replace the color aes with a new aes called group. In other words, map the group aesthetic to the city aesthetic.

us_three %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_line(aes(x = year, y = population, group = city))

You should now see three lines that are all in black. It is this exact plot that was being colored in the previous example.

Whatâ€™s going on here? When we add aesthetics such as color and size to a line geometry, another aesthetic called group is magically set at the same time. It is possible to set this aesthetic explicitly if we want to group the data without producing a different size or color.

Fixed Aesthetics

Now, return again to the cities dataset. Produce a scatter plot with longitude and latitude, but color all of the points the color â€œpinkâ€.

cities %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_point(aes(x = lon, y = lat), color = "pink")

Starting from the plot in the previous question, modify the size of the points to change with the population of each city.

cities %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_point(aes(x = lon, y = lat, size = population), color = "pink")

Another aesthetic value that was not covered in the notes above is alpha. It is given by a number between 0 and 1 and sets how opaque the points are shown. Most typically it is used as a fixed aesthetic to make a plot with a large number of points more readable. Starting with the plot in the previous question, add a fixed aesthetic to change the alpha value of the points to 0.4.

cities %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_point(
      aes(x = lon, y = lat, size = population),
      color = "pink",
      alpha = 0.4
    )

Notice how the areas where multiple cities overlap are darker than the surrounding regions.

Scales

With the cities dataset, produce a scatter plot with city area (city_area) on the x-axis and city population (city_pop) on the y-axis.

cities %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_point(aes(x = city_area, y = city_pop))

You should find that it is difficult to interpret this plot because most of the cities are squished together on the left-side of the plot. One way to fix this is to use a logarithmic scale. In the code block below, provide a modification of this plot with logarithmic scales for the x- and y-axes.

cities %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_point(aes(x = city_area, y = city_pop)) +
    scale_x_log10() +
    scale_y_log10()

You should find this plot easier to work with. If you are not familiar with the scientific notation used on the x-axis labels here, make sure to learn more about these as they will appear from time-to-time throughout the notes in this course.

Color Scales

The KÃ¶ppen climate classification is a way of describing the climate of a region or city. Information about these scores are included in the cities dataset and are something that we will explore in length in future notebooks. Here we will work with the four level categorization stored in the variable koppen_main (there are actually five levels, but the coldest level is not present in this dataset).

In the code block below, produce a scatter plot of the cities dataset with longitude on the x-axis and latitude on the y-axis. Color the points based on the koppen_main variable.

cities %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_point(aes(x = lon, y = lat, color = koppen_main))

In the code below, modify this plot to use the color-blind friendly Viridis color scale:

cities %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_point(aes(x = lon, y = lat, color = koppen_main)) +
    scale_color_viridis_d()

There is a well-known and standardized color scale for the KÃ¶ppen codes. We will use the full palette in a future notebook; here we will just set values for the four main categories. In the code below repeat the scatterplot, but add a manual color scale where the â€œTropicalâ€ climates are blue, the â€œDryâ€ climates are red, â€œTemperateâ€ is green and â€œContinentalâ€ is purple.

cities %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_point(aes(x = lon, y = lat, color = koppen_main)) +
    scale_color_manual(values = c(
      Tropical = "blue",
      Dry = "red",
      Temperate = "green",
      Continental = "purple"
    ))
